JГғВіzsef KГғВјrschГғВЎk 's mother was Jozefa Teller and his father was AndrГғВЎs KГғВјrschГғВЎk, a manual worker who died when JГғВіzsef was six years old. After the death of his father, JГғВіzsef was brought up in Budapest by his mother. It is correct to say that JГғВіzsef, although born in Buda, was brought up in Budapest after the death of his father since Budapest was created by the unification of Buda, Obuda and Pest in 1872 . KГғВјrschГғВЎk attended secondary school in the flourishing city that became not only the capital of Hungary but also a major centre for industry, trade, communications, and architecture. Most importantly for the young boy, he was growing up in a city which was a centre for education, and for intellectual and artistic life.
KГғВјrschГғВЎk entered the Technical University of Budapest in 1881 and graduated in 1886 with qualifications to teach mathematics and physics in secondary schools. He then taught at a school in Roznyo, Slovakia, for two years before returning to the Technical University of Budapest to undertake research. He received his doctorate in 1890 and then taught in Budapest, at the Technical University, for the whole of his career. He was appointed in 1891 and successively promoted, achieving the rank of professor in 1900 .
In [ 2 ] the authors describe a paper by KГғВјrschГғВЎk written in 1898 in which a regular dodecagon inscribed in a unit circle is investigated. A trigonometric argument can be used to show that its area of the dodecagon is 3 but KГғВјrschГғВЎk gives a purely geometric proof. He proves that the dodecagon can be dissected into a set of triangles which can be rearranged so as to fill three squares with sides having length 1 . KГғВјrschГғВЎk's tile, which occurs in the title of [ 2 ] , is constructed as follows. Start with a square and construct an equilateral triangle drawn inwards on each side. A regular dodecagon has the following 12 points as vertices: the 8 intersections of the corresponding sides of adjacent equilateral triangles and the 4 mid-points of the sides of the new square formed by the vertices of the four triangles. In fact the first paper which KГғВјrschГғВЎk wrote was concerned with polygons. This was ГғВңber dem Kreise ein-und umgeschriebene Vielecke ГўВ“Вү ( On the circles on  rewritten polygons ) (1887) which investigated extremal properties of polygons inscribed in, and circumscribed about, a circle.
Another topic which KГғВјrschГғВЎk investigated was the differential equations of the calculus of variations. Papers such as ГғВңber partielle Differentialgleichungen zweiter Ordnung mit gleichen Charakteristiken ГўВ“Вү ( On partial differential equations of second order with the same characteristics ) (1890) , ГғВңber die partielle Differentialgleichung des Problems ГўВ“Вү ( On the partial differential equation of the problem ) (1894) , ГғВңber die Transformation der partiellen Differentialgleichungen der Variationsrechnung ГўВ“Вү ( On the transformation of partial differential equations of the calculus of variations ) (1902) , and ГғВңber eine charakteristische Eigenschaft der Differentialgleichungen der Variationsrechnung ГўВ“Вү ( On a characteristic property of the differential equations of the calculus of variations ) (1905) are examples of his work in this area. He proved invariance of the differential equations he was considering under contact transformations. Another problem he solved in this area was to find, in his 1905 paper, necessary and sufficient conditions for [ 1 ] :- ... a second-order differential expressions to provide the equation belonging to the variation of a multiple integral. Led to consider linear algebra in the context of the above work, he wrote a number of papers on matrices and determinants such as ГғВңber symmetrische Matrices ГўВ“Вү ( On symmetric matrices ) (1904) and Ein irreduzibilitГғВӨtssatz in der Theorie der symmetrischen matrizen ГўВ“Вү ( An irreducibility theorem in the theory of symmetric matrices ) (1921) .
